<subSubSection id="C30AB4B0F553FF8EB582D3A5FED1CD41" pageId="9" pageNumber="310" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8BAFE73BF553FF8EB582D3A5FED1CD41" blockId="9.[151,1437,1525,1767]" pageId="9" pageNumber="310">
<emphasis id="B9643B29F553FF8EB582D3A5FE94CD35" bold="true" box="[151,273,1525,1550]" pageId="9" pageNumber="310">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Females can be distinguished by the anterior ridge arched and thick on the sides (
<figureCitation id="132BFBBEF553FF8EB1C8D3A5FABCCD35" box="[1245,1337,1525,1550]" captionStart="FIGURE 10" captionStartId="15.[151,250,1772,1794]" captionTargetBox="[154,1432,193,1750]" captionTargetId="figure@15.[151,1436,193,1750]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURE 10. Apopyllus spp., epigynum, ventral view, drawings. Vulva can be seen by transparency. A A. silvestrii (MCTP 26293). B A. suavis (MNRJ 58361). C A. malleco (AMNH). D A. huanuco (AMNH). E A. now (MCZ 24971). F A. gandarela new. sp. (UFMG 16876). G A. centralis new sp. (UFMG 4564). H A. atlanticus new sp. (MCTP 27338)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/261083/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="310">Figs 10</figureCitation>
E, 11E). Males can be diagnosed by the retrolateral cymbial projection shorter than the RTA in dorsal and ventral view, by the shorter embolus, with a more distally situated embolus loop, and by the shape of the robust RTA (
<figureCitation id="132BFBBEF553FF8EB018D06DFAD1CD6D" box="[1293,1364,1597,1622]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1201,1223]" captionTargetBox="[171,1436,224,1147]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[151,1436,209,1147]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 3. Apopyllus spp., male left palp in ventral view, drawings. A A. silvestrii (MCTP 26293). B A. suavis (IBSP 129024). C A. now (MCZ 22335). D A. ivieorum (AMNH). E A. aeolicus new. sp. (CHNUFPI 1567). F A. centralis new sp. (UFMG 4395). G A. atlanticus new sp. (UFMG 16828)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/261076/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="310">Figs 3</figureCitation>
C, 4C, 5C, 6C, 7C, 8C).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
